# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: genetics-fundamentals
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:genetics-fundamentals/allele] An **allele** is a variant of the sequence of nucleotides at a particular location, or locus, on a DNA molecule.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/allele] Alleles can differ at a single position through single-nucleotide polymorphisms, but they can also have insertions and deletions of up to several thousand base pairs.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/allele] Most alleles result in little or no change in the characteristics of an individual organism but sometimes different alleles can result in different observable phenotypic traits such as antibiotic resistance in bacteria, developmental mutations in fruit flies, and genetic diseases in humans.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/allele] Nearly all multicellular organisms have two sets of chromosomes at some point in their biological life cycle; that is, they are diploid.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/allele] For a given locus, if the two chromosomes contain the same allele, they, and the organism, are homozygous with respect to that allele.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/allele] If the alleles are different, they, and the organism, are heterozygous with respect to those alleles.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/allele] A notable example of this is Gregor Mendel's discovery that the white and purple flower colors in pea plants were the result of a single gene with two alleles.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/allele] Mendel's discovery of what are now known as alleles resulted in three laws that help understand how alleles are passed on to progeny.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/allele] Popular definitions of 'allele' typically refer only to different alleles within genes.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/allele] For example, the ABO blood grouping is controlled by the ABO gene, which has six common alleles (variants).
[src:genetics-fundamentals/allele] In population genetics, nearly every living human's phenotype for the ABO gene is some combination of just these six alleles.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/allele] It derives from the Greek prefix ἀλληλο-, *allelo-*, meaning "mutual", "reciprocal", or "each other", which itself is related to the Greek adjective ἄλλος, *allos* (cognate with Latin *alius*), meaning "other".
[src:genetics-fundamentals/allele] In many cases, genotypic interactions between the two alleles at a locus can be described as dominant or recessive, according to which of the two homozygous phenotypes the heterozygote most resembles.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/allele] Where the heterozygote is indistinguishable from one of the homozygotes, the allele expressed is the one that leads to the "dominant" phenotype, and the other allele is said to be "recessive".
[src:genetics-fundamentals/allele] In the case of a heterozygote, the dominant allele will mask the effect of the recessive allele, giving a dominant phenotype.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/allele] The phenotype of recessive alleles are observable when an organism is homozygous recessive for a gene.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/allele] The degree and pattern of dominance varies among loci.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/allele] This type of interaction was first formally-described by Gregor Mendel.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/allele] However, many traits defy this simple categorization and the phenotypes are modelled by co-dominance and polygenic inheritance.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/allele] The term "wild type" allele is sometimes used to describe an allele that is thought to contribute to the typical phenotypic character as seen in "wild" populations of organisms, such as fruit flies (*Drosophila melanogaster*).
[src:genetics-fundamentals/allele] Such a "wild type" allele was historically regarded as leading to a dominant (overpowering – always expressed), common, and normal phenotype, in contrast to "mutant" alleles that lead to recessive, rare, and frequently deleterious phenotypes.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/allele] It is now appreciated that most or all gene loci are highly polymorphic, with multiple alleles, whose frequencies vary from population to population, and that a great deal of genetic variation is hidden in the form of alleles that do not produce obvious phenotypic differences.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/allele] Wild type alleles are often denoted by a superscript plus sign (*i.e.*, *p+* for an allele *p*).
[src:genetics-fundamentals/allele] A population or species of organisms typically includes multiple alleles at each locus among various individuals.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/allele] Allelic variation at a locus is measurable as the number of alleles (polymorphism) present, or the proportion of heterozygotes in the population.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/allele] A null allele is a gene variant that lacks the gene's normal function because it either is not expressed, or the expressed protein is inactive.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/allele] For example, at the gene locus for the ABO blood type carbohydrate antigens in humans, classical genetics recognizes three alleles, IA, IB, and i, which determine compatibility of blood transfusions.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/allele] (It is now known that each of the A, B, and O alleles is actually a class of multiple alleles with different DNA sequences that produce proteins with identical properties: more than 70 alleles are known at the ABO locus.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/allele] The frequency of alleles in a diploid population can be used to predict the frequencies of the corresponding genotypes (see Hardy–Weinberg principle).
[src:genetics-fundamentals/allele] where *p* is the frequency of one allele and *q* is the frequency of the alternative allele, which necessarily sum to unity.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/allele] Then, *p*2 is the fraction of the population homozygous for the first allele, 2*pq* is the fraction of heterozygotes, and *q*2 is the fraction homozygous for the alternative allele.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/allele] If the first allele is dominant to the second then the fraction of the population that will show the dominant phenotype is *p*2 + 2*pq*, and the fraction with the recessive phenotype is *q*2.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/allele] A number of genetic disorders are caused when an individual inherits two recessive alleles for a single-gene trait.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/allele] Recessive genetic disorders include albinism, cystic fibrosis, galactosemia, phenylketonuria (PKU), and Tay–Sachs disease.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/allele] Other disorders are also due to recessive alleles, but because the gene locus is located on the X chromosome, so that males have only one copy (that is, they are hemizygous), they are more frequent in males than in females.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/allele] Examples include red–green color blindness and fragile X syndrome.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/allele] Other disorders, such as Huntington's disease, occur when an individual inherits only one dominant allele.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/allele] While heritable traits are typically studied in terms of genetic alleles, epigenetic marks such as DNA methylation can be inherited at specific genomic regions in certain species, a process termed transgenerational epigenetic inheritance.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/allele] The term *epiallele* is used to distinguish these heritable marks from traditional alleles, which are defined by nucleotide sequence.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/allele] A specific class of epiallele, the metastable epialleles, has been discovered in mice and in humans which is characterized by stochastic (probabilistic) establishment of epigenetic state that can be mitotically inherited.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/allele] The term "idiomorph", from Greek 'morphos' (form) and 'idio' (singular, unique), was introduced in 1990 in place of "allele" to denote sequences at the same locus in different strains that have no sequence similarity and probably do not share a common phylogenetic relationship.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/allele] It is used mainly in the genetic research of mycology.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/dominance-genetics] In genetics, **dominance** is the phenomenon of one variant (allele) of a gene on a chromosome masking or overriding the effect of a different variant of the same gene on the other copy of the chromosome.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/dominance-genetics] The masking or overriding variant is said to be ***dominant*** and the other ***recessive***.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/dominance-genetics] This state of having two different variants of the same gene, one on each copy of the chromosome, is originally caused by a mutation in one of the genes, either new (*de novo*) or inherited.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/dominance-genetics] Since there is only one Y chromosome, Y-linked traits cannot be dominant or recessive.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/dominance-genetics] Additionally, there are other forms of dominance, such as **incomplete dominance**, in which a gene variant has a partial effect compared to when it is present on both chromosomes, and **co-dominance**, in which different variants on each chromosome both show their associated traits.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/dominance-genetics] Dominance is a key concept in Mendelian inheritance and classical genetics.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/dominance-genetics] Letters and Punnett squares are used to demonstrate the principles of dominance in teaching, and the upper-case letters are used to denote dominant alleles and lower-case letters are used for recessive alleles.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/dominance-genetics] An often quoted example of dominance is the inheritance of seed shape in peas.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/dominance-genetics] Peas may be round, associated with allele ***R***, or wrinkled, associated with allele *r*.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/dominance-genetics] In this case, three combinations of alleles (genotypes) are possible: ***RR***, ***Rr***, and ***rr***.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/dominance-genetics] The ***RR*** (homozygous) individuals have round peas, and the ***rr*** (homozygous) individuals have wrinkled peas.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/dominance-genetics] In ***Rr*** (heterozygous) individuals, the ***R*** allele masks the presence of the *r* allele, so these individuals also have round peas.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/dominance-genetics] Thus, allele ***R*** is dominant over allele ***r***, and allele ***r*** is recessive to allele ***R***.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/dominance-genetics] Dominance is not inherent to an allele or its traits (phenotype).
[src:genetics-fundamentals/dominance-genetics] It is a strictly relative effect between two alleles of a given gene of any function; one allele can be dominant over a second allele of the same gene, recessive to a third, and co-dominant with a fourth.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/dominance-genetics] Additionally, one allele may be dominant for one trait but not others.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/dominance-genetics] Dominance differs from epistasis, the phenomenon of an allele of one gene masking the effect of alleles of a *different* gene.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/dominance-genetics] Gregor Johann Mendel, "The Father of Genetics", promulgated the idea of dominance in the 1860s.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/dominance-genetics] However, it was not widely known until the early twentieth century.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/dominance-genetics] Mendel observed that, for a variety of traits of garden peas having to do with the appearance of seeds, seed pods, and plants, there were two discrete phenotypes, such as round versus wrinkled seeds, yellow versus green seeds, red versus white flowers or tall versus short plants.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/dominance-genetics] When bred separately, the plants always produced the same phenotypes, generation after generation.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/dominance-genetics] However, when lines with different phenotypes were crossed (interbred), one and only one of the parental phenotypes showed up in the offspring (green, round, red, or tall).
[src:genetics-fundamentals/dominance-genetics] However, when these hybrid plants were crossed, the offspring plants showed the two original phenotypes, in a characteristic 3:1 ratio, the more common phenotype being that of the parental hybrid plants.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/dominance-genetics] The final cross between two heterozygotes (Aa X Aa) would produce AA, Aa, and aa offspring in a 1:2:1 genotype ratio with the first two classes showing the (A) phenotype, and the last showing the (a) phenotype, thereby producing the 3:1 phenotype ratio.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/dominance-genetics] Mendel did not use the terms *gene*, *allele*, *phenotype*, *genotype*, *homozygote*, and *heterozygote*, all of which were introduced later.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/dominance-genetics] He did introduce the notation of capital and lowercase letters for dominant and recessive alleles, respectively, still in use today.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/dominance-genetics] In 1928, British population geneticist Ronald Fisher proposed that dominance acted based on natural selection through the contribution of modifier genes.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/dominance-genetics] In 1929, American geneticist Sewall Wright responded by stating that dominance is simply a physiological consequence of metabolic pathways and the relative necessity of the gene involved.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/dominance-genetics] In complete dominance, the effect of one allele in a heterozygous genotype completely masks the effect of the other.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/dominance-genetics] The allele that masks are considered *dominant* to the other allele, and the masked allele is considered *recessive*.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/dominance-genetics] When we only look at one trait determined by one pair of genes, we call it **monohybrid inheritance**.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/dominance-genetics] If the crossing is done between parents (P-generation, F0-generation) who are homozygote dominant and homozygote recessive, the offspring (F1-generation) will always have the heterozygote genotype and always present the phenotype associated with the dominant gene.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/dominance-genetics] However, if the F1-generation is further crossed with the F1-generation (heterozygote crossed with heterozygote) the offspring (F2-generation) will present the phenotype associated with the dominant gene ¾ times.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/dominance-genetics] Although heterozygote monohybrid crossing can result in two phenotype variants, it can result in three genotype variants - homozygote dominant, heterozygote and homozygote recessive, respectively.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/dominance-genetics] In **dihybrid inheritance** we look at the inheritance of two pairs of genes simultaneously.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/dominance-genetics] Assuming here that the two pairs of genes are located at non-homologous chromosomes, such that they are not coupled genes (see genetic linkage) but instead inherited independently.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/dominance-genetics] Consider now the cross between parents (P-generation) of genotypes homozygote dominant and recessive, respectively.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/dominance-genetics] The offspring (F1-generation) will always heterozygous and present the phenotype associated with the dominant allele variant.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/dominance-genetics] However, when crossing the F1-generation there are four possible phenotypic possibilities and the phenotypical ratio for the F2-generation will always be 9:3:3:1.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/dominance-genetics] The phenotypic result often appears as a blended form of characteristics in the heterozygous state.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/dominance-genetics] For example, the snapdragon flower color is homozygous for either red or white.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/dominance-genetics] When the red homozygous flower is paired with the white homozygous flower, the result yields a pink snapdragon flower.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/dominance-genetics] The pink snapdragon is the result of incomplete dominance.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/dominance-genetics] A similar type of incomplete dominance is found in the four o'clock plant wherein pink color is produced when true-bred parents of white and red flowers are crossed.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/dominance-genetics] When plants of the F1 generation are self-pollinated, the phenotypic and genotypic ratio of the F2 generation will be 1:2:1 (Red:Pink:White).
[src:genetics-fundamentals/dominance-genetics] Co-dominance occurs when the contributions of both alleles are visible in the phenotype and neither allele masks another.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/dominance-genetics] For example, in the ABO blood group system, chemical modifications to a glycoprotein (the H antigen) on the surfaces of blood cells are controlled by three alleles, two of which are co-dominant to each other (*IA*, *IB*) and dominant over the recessive *i* at the ABO locus.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/dominance-genetics] The *IA* and *IB* alleles produce different modifications.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/dominance-genetics] The enzyme coded for by *IA* adds an N-acetylgalactosamine to a membrane-bound H antigen.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/dominance-genetics] The *i* allele produces no modification.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/dominance-genetics] Another example occurs at the locus for the beta-globin component of hemoglobin, where the three molecular phenotypes of *HbA/HbA*, *HbA/HbS*, and *HbS/HbS* are all distinguishable by protein electrophoresis.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/dominance-genetics] (The medical condition produced by the heterozygous genotype is called *sickle-cell trait* and is a milder condition distinguishable from *sickle-cell anemia*, thus the alleles show *incomplete dominance* concerning anemia, see above).
[src:genetics-fundamentals/dominance-genetics] For most gene loci at the molecular level, both alleles are expressed co-dominantly, because both are transcribed into RNA.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/dominance-genetics] Co-dominance, where allelic products co-exist in the phenotype, is different from incomplete dominance, where the quantitative interaction of allele products produces an intermediate phenotype.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/dominance-genetics] For example, in co-dominance, a red homozygous flower and a white homozygous flower will produce offspring that have red and white spots.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/dominance-genetics] When plants of the F1 generation are self-pollinated, the phenotypic and genotypic ratio of the F2 generation will be 1:2:1 (Red:Spotted:White).
[src:genetics-fundamentals/dominance-genetics] These ratios are the same as those for incomplete dominance.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/dominance-genetics] Again, this classical terminology is inappropriate – in reality, such cases should not be said to exhibit dominance at all.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/dominance-genetics] Dominance can be influenced by various genetic interactions and it is essential to evaluate them when determining phenotypic outcomes.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/dominance-genetics] Multiple alleles, epistasis, pleiotropic genes, and polygenic characteristics are some factors that might influence the phenotypic outcome.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/dominance-genetics] Although any individual of a diploid organism has at most two different alleles at a given locus, most genes exist in a large number of allelic versions in the population as a whole.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/dominance-genetics] This is called polymorphism, and is caused by mutations.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/dominance-genetics] Polymorphism can have an effect on the dominance relationship and phenotype, which is observed in the ABO blood group system.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/dominance-genetics] The gene responsible for human blood type have three alleles; A, B, and O, and their interactions result in different blood types based on the level of dominance the alleles expresses towards each other.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/dominance-genetics] Epistasis is interactions between multiple alleles at different loci.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/dominance-genetics] More specifically, epistasis is when one gene can mask the phenotype of a gene at a completely different locus.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/dominance-genetics] Therefore, several genes can influence the phenotype expressed.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/dominance-genetics] Epistasis is slightly different from dominance in the fact that dominance is an allele-to-allele interaction at one locus while epistasis is a gene-to-gene interaction at different loci.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/dominance-genetics] The dominance relationship between alleles involved in epistatic interactions can influence the observed phenotypic ratios in offspring.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/dominance-genetics] An example of epistasis can be seen in Labrador retriever coat colors.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/dominance-genetics] One gene at one locus codes for the color of hair but another gene at a different locus determines if the color is even deposited in the hair.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/dominance-genetics] Recessive epistasis is seen in this example due to recessive alleles for color desposition masking both the dominant black (B) allele and recessive brown (b) allele at the first locus to express a yellow coat in the Labrador retriever.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/dominance-genetics] The yellow color comes from no pigment being deposited in the hair shaft.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/dominance-genetics] Other examples of epistasis interactions are dominant epistasis and duplicate recessive epistasis.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/dominance-genetics] Each type of epistasis is a modification of the dihyrbid ratio of 9:3:3:1.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/dominance-genetics] Pleiotropic genes are genes where one single gene affects two or more characteristics.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/dominance-genetics] An example of this concept is Marfan Syndrome which is a mutation of the FBN1 gene.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/dominance-genetics] The effects this causes are a person's appearance being tall and long limbed.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/dominance-genetics] They can also have Scoliosis, Ectopia Lentis, and larger than normal aortas.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/dominance-genetics] Pleiotropy shares a relationship with Epistasis.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/dominance-genetics] While pleiotropy represents one single gene, epistasis is multiple genes interacting with one another to cause different traits to arise. it is helpful to recognize how Epistasis could affect viewing pleiotropic genes if different traits arise or mask themselves to varying degrees.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/dominance-genetics] Polygenic characteristics are those affected by multiple genes at different loci.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/dominance-genetics] These different genes interact in a way to produce a quantitative characteristic, which is a characteristic that presents a wide variety phenotypes, such as height in humans.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/dominance-genetics] The greater the number of genes that interact to influence this characteristic, the greater the number of different phenotypes possible due to more possible genotypes.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/dominance-genetics] Many more characteristics also appear to be affected by more than one gene located on different loci, including diabetes and some autoimmune diseases.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetic-linkage] Genetic linkage is the most prominent exception to Gregor Mendel's Law of Independent Assortment.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetic-linkage] The first experiment to demonstrate linkage was carried out in 1905.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetic-linkage] At the time, the reason why certain traits tend to be inherited together was unknown.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetic-linkage] Later work revealed that genes are physical structures related by physical distance.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetic-linkage] The typical unit of genetic linkage is the centimorgan (cM).
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetic-linkage] A distance of 1 cM between two markers means that the markers are separated to different chromosomes on average once per 100 meiotic product, thus once per 50 meioses.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetic-linkage] Gregor Mendel's Law of Independent Assortment states that every trait is inherited independently of every other trait.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetic-linkage] But shortly after Mendel's work was rediscovered, exceptions to this rule were found.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetic-linkage] In 1905, the British geneticists William Bateson, Edith Rebecca Saunders and Reginald Punnett cross-bred pea plants in experiments similar to Mendel's.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetic-linkage] They were interested in trait inheritance in the sweet pea and were studying two genes—the gene for flower colour (*P*, purple, and *p*, red) and the gene affecting the shape of pollen grains (*L*, long, and *l*, round).
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetic-linkage] They crossed the pure lines *PPLL* and *ppll* and then self-crossed the resulting *PpLl* lines.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetic-linkage] According to Mendelian genetics, the expected phenotypes would occur in a 9:3:3:1 ratio of PL:Pl:pL:pl.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetic-linkage] Their experiment revealed linkage between the *P* and *L* alleles and the *p* and *l* alleles.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetic-linkage] The frequency of *P* occurring together with *L* and *p* occurring together with *l* is greater than that of the recombinant *Pl* and *pL*.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetic-linkage] The recombination frequency is more difficult to compute in an F2 cross than a backcross, but the lack of fit between observed and expected numbers of progeny in the above table indicate it is less than 50%.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetic-linkage] This indicated that two factors interacted in some way to create this difference by masking the appearance of the other two phenotypes.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetic-linkage] This led to the conclusion that some traits are related to each other because of their near proximity to each other on a chromosome.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetic-linkage] The understanding of linkage was expanded by the work of Thomas Hunt Morgan.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetic-linkage] Morgan's observation that the amount of crossing over between linked genes differs led to the idea that crossover frequency might indicate the distance separating genes on the chromosome.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetic-linkage] The centimorgan, which expresses the frequency of crossing over, is named in his honour.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetic-linkage] A **linkage map** (also known as a **genetic map**) is a table for a species or experimental population that shows the position of its known genes or genetic markers relative to each other in terms of recombination frequency, rather than a specific physical distance along each chromosome.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetic-linkage] Linkage maps were first developed by Alfred Sturtevant, a student of Thomas Hunt Morgan.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetic-linkage] A linkage map is a map based on the frequencies of recombination between markers during crossover of homologous chromosomes.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetic-linkage] The greater the frequency of recombination (segregation) between two genetic markers, the further apart they are assumed to be.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetic-linkage] Conversely, the lower the frequency of recombination between the markers, the smaller the physical distance between them.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetic-linkage] Linkage maps help researchers to locate other markers, such as other genes by testing for genetic linkage of the already known markers.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetic-linkage] In the early stages of developing a linkage map, the data are used to assemble **linkage groups**, a set of genes which are known to be linked.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetic-linkage] As knowledge advances, more markers can be added to a group, until the group covers an entire chromosome.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetic-linkage] For well-studied organisms the linkage groups correspond one-to-one with the chromosomes.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetic-linkage] A linkage map is **not** a physical map (such as a radiation reduced hybrid map) or gene map.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetic-linkage] Linkage analysis is a genetic method that searches for chromosomal segments that cosegregate with the ailment phenotype through families.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetic-linkage] It can be used to map genes for both binary and quantitative traits.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetic-linkage] Linkage analysis may be either parametric (if we know the relationship between phenotypic and genetic similarity) or non-parametric.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetic-linkage] Non-parametric linkage analysis, in turn, studies the probability of an allele being identical by descent with itself.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetic-linkage] The **LOD score** (logarithm (base 10) of odds), developed by Newton Morton, is a statistical test often used for linkage analysis in human, animal, and plant populations.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetic-linkage] The LOD score compares the likelihood of obtaining the test data if the two loci are indeed linked, to the likelihood of observing the same data purely by chance (that is, it is (the log of) the likelihood ratio).
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetic-linkage] Thus, one can add the LOD score to the log odds of the prior probability for the hypothesis to update it to the posterior log odds as prescribed by Bayes' law.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetic-linkage] That is, LOD scores are precisely the strength of evidence (in base 10 instead of bits) for linkage of an amount equal to the observed amount (essentially, a maximum likelihood or maximum a posteriori value).
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetic-linkage] Positive LOD scores favour the presence of linkage, whereas negative LOD scores indicate that linkage is less likely.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetic-linkage] Computerised LOD score analysis is a simple way to analyse complex family pedigrees in order to determine the linkage between Mendelian traits (or between a trait and a marker, or two markers).
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetic-linkage] NR denotes the number of non-recombinant offspring, and R denotes the number of recombinant offspring.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetic-linkage] The reason 0.5 is used in the denominator is that any alleles that are completely unlinked (e.g. alleles on separate chromosomes) have a 50% chance of recombination, due to independent assortment.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetic-linkage] *θ* is the recombinant fraction, i.e. the fraction of births in which recombination has happened between the studied genetic marker and the putative gene associated with the disease.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetic-linkage] By convention, a LOD score greater than 3.0 is considered evidence for linkage, as it indicates 1000 to 1 odds that the linkage being observed did not occur by chance.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetic-linkage] On the other hand, a LOD score less than −2.0 is considered evidence to exclude linkage.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetic-linkage] Although it is very unlikely that a LOD score of 3 would be obtained from a single pedigree, the mathematical properties of the test allow data from a number of pedigrees to be combined by summing their LOD scores.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetic-linkage] A LOD score of 3 translates to a *p*-value of approximately 0.05, and no multiple testing correction (e.g.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetic-linkage] Linkage analysis has a number of methodological and theoretical limitations that can significantly increase the type-1 error rate and reduce the power to map human quantitative trait loci (QTL).
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetic-linkage] While linkage analysis was successfully used to identify genetic variants that contribute to rare disorders such as Huntington disease, it did not perform that well when applied to more common disorders such as heart disease or different forms of cancer.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetic-linkage] An explanation for this is that the genetic mechanisms affecting common disorders are different from those causing some rare disorders.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetic-linkage] Recombination frequency is a measure of genetic linkage and is used in the creation of a genetic linkage map.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetic-linkage] Recombination frequency (*θ*) is the frequency with which a single chromosomal crossover will take place between two genes during meiosis.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetic-linkage] A centimorgan (cM) is a unit that describes a recombination frequency of 1%.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetic-linkage] In this way we can measure the genetic distance between two loci, based upon their recombination frequency.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetic-linkage] This is a good estimate of the real distance.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetic-linkage] Double crossovers would turn into no recombination.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetic-linkage] In this case we cannot tell if crossovers took place.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetic-linkage] If the loci we're analysing are very close (less than 7 cM) a double crossover is very unlikely.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetic-linkage] When distances become higher, the likelihood of a double crossover increases.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetic-linkage] As the likelihood of a double crossover increases one could systematically underestimate the genetic distance between two loci, unless one used an appropriate mathematical model.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetic-linkage] Double linkage is more of a historical concern for plants.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetic-linkage] In animals, double crossover happens rarely.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetic-linkage] In humans, for example, one chromosome has two crossovers on average during meiosis.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetic-linkage] Furthermore, modern geneticists have enough genes that only nearby genes need to be linkage-analyzed, unlike the early days when only a few genes were known.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetic-linkage] During meiosis, chromosomes assort randomly into gametes, such that the segregation of alleles of one gene is independent of alleles of another gene.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetic-linkage] This is stated in Mendel's Second Law and is known as **the law of independent assortment**.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetic-linkage] The law of independent assortment always holds true for genes that are located on different chromosomes, but for genes that are on the same chromosome, it does not always hold true.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetic-linkage] As an example of independent assortment, consider the crossing of the pure-bred homozygote parental strain with genotype *AABB* with a different pure-bred strain with genotype *aabb*.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetic-linkage] A and a and B and b represent the alleles of genes A and B.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetic-linkage] Crossing these homozygous parental strains will result in F1 generation offspring that are double heterozygotes with genotype AaBb.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetic-linkage] The F1 offspring AaBb produces gametes that are *AB*, *Ab*, *aB*, and *ab* with equal frequencies (25%) because the alleles of gene A assort independently of the alleles for gene B during meiosis.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetic-linkage] Note that 2 of the 4 gametes (50%)—*Ab* and *aB*—were not present in the parental generation.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetic-linkage] These gametes represent **recombinant gametes**.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetic-linkage] Recombinant gametes are those gametes that differ from both of the haploid gametes that made up the original diploid cell.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetic-linkage] In this example, the recombination frequency is 50% since 2 of the 4 gametes were recombinant gametes.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetic-linkage] The recombination frequency will be 50% when two genes are located on different chromosomes or when they are widely separated on the same chromosome.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetic-linkage] This is a consequence of independent assortment.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetic-linkage] When two genes are close together on the same chromosome, they do not assort independently and are said to be linked.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetic-linkage] Whereas genes located on different chromosomes assort independently and have a recombination frequency of 50%, linked genes have a recombination frequency that is less than 50%.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetic-linkage] As an example of linkage, consider the classic experiment by William Bateson and Reginald Punnett.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetic-linkage] To their surprise, they observed an increased frequency of PL and pl and a decreased frequency of Pl and pL (see table below).
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetic-linkage] Their experiment revealed **linkage** between the *P* and *L* alleles and the *p* and *l* alleles.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetic-linkage] The frequency of *P* occurring together with *L* and with *p* occurring together with *l* is greater than that of the recombinant *Pl* and *pL*.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetic-linkage] The progeny in this case received two dominant alleles linked on one chromosome (referred to as **coupling** or **cis arrangement**).
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetic-linkage] However, after crossover, some progeny could have received one parental chromosome with a dominant allele for one trait (e.g.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetic-linkage] Purple) linked to a recessive allele for a second trait (e.g. round) with the opposite being true for the other parental chromosome (e.g. red and Long).
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetic-linkage] This is referred to as **repulsion** or a **trans arrangement**.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetic-linkage] The phenotype here would still be purple and long but a test cross of this individual with the recessive parent would produce progeny with much greater proportion of the two crossover phenotypes.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetic-linkage] While such a problem may not seem likely from this example, unfavourable repulsion linkages do appear when breeding for disease resistance in some crops.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetic-linkage] The two possible arrangements, cis and trans, of alleles in a double heterozygote are referred to as gametic phases, and *phasing* is the process of determining which of the two is present in a given individual.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetic-linkage] When two genes are located on the same chromosome, the chance of a crossover producing recombination between the genes is related to the distance between the two genes.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetic-linkage] Thus, the use of recombination frequencies has been used to develop **linkage maps** or **genetic maps**.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetic-linkage] However, recombination frequency tends to underestimate the distance between two linked genes.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetic-linkage] This is because as the two genes are located farther apart, the chance of double or even number of crossovers between them also increases.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetic-linkage] Double or even number of crossovers between the two genes results in them being cosegregated to the same gamete, yielding a parental progeny instead of the expected recombinant progeny.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetic-linkage] As mentioned above, the Kosambi and Haldane transformations attempt to correct for multiple crossovers.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetic-linkage] In the early 1950s the prevailing view was that the genes in a chromosome are discrete entities, indivisible by genetic recombination and arranged like beads on a string.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetic-linkage] During 1955 to 1959, Benzer performed genetic recombination experiments using rII mutants of bacteriophage T4.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetic-linkage] He found that, on the basis of recombination tests, the sites of mutation could be mapped in a linear order.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetic-linkage] This result provided evidence for the key idea that the gene has a linear structure equivalent to a length of DNA with many sites that can independently mutate.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetic-linkage] Edgar et al. performed mapping experiments with r mutants of bacteriophage T4 showing that recombination frequencies between rII mutants are not strictly additive.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetic-linkage] The recombination frequency from a cross of two rII mutants (a x d) is usually less than the sum of recombination frequencies for adjacent internal sub-intervals (a x b) + (b x c) + (c x d).
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetic-linkage] Although not strictly additive, a systematic relationship was observed that likely reflects the underlying molecular mechanism of genetic recombination.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetic-linkage] While recombination of chromosomes is an essential process during meiosis, there is a large range of frequency of cross overs across organisms and within species.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetic-linkage] Sexually dimorphic rates of recombination are termed heterochiasmy, and are observed more often than a common rate between male and females.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetic-linkage] In mammals, females often have a higher rate of recombination compared to males.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetic-linkage] It is theorised that there are unique selections acting or meiotic drivers which influence the difference in rates.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetic-linkage] The difference in rates may also reflect the vastly different environments and conditions of meiosis in oogenesis and spermatogenesis.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetic-linkage] Mutations in genes that encode proteins involved in the processing of DNA often affect recombination frequency.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetic-linkage] In bacteriophage T4, mutations that reduce expression of the replicative DNA polymerase [gene product 43 (gp43)] increase recombination (decrease linkage) several fold.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetic-linkage] The increase in recombination may be due to replication errors by the defective DNA polymerase that are themselves recombination events such as template switches, i.e. copy choice recombination events.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetic-linkage] Recombination is also increased by mutations that reduce the expression of DNA ligase (gp30) and dCMP hydroxymethylase (gp42), two enzymes employed in DNA synthesis.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetic-linkage] Recombination is reduced (linkage increased) by mutations in genes that encode proteins with nuclease functions (gp46 and gp47) and a DNA-binding protein (gp32) Mutation in the bacteriophage uvsX gene also substantially reduces recombination.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetic-linkage] The uvsX gene is analogous to the well studied *recA* gene of *Escherichia coli* that plays a central role in recombination.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetic-linkage] With very large pedigrees or with very dense genetic marker data, such as from whole-genome sequencing, it is possible to precisely locate recombinations.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetic-linkage] With this type of genetic analysis, a meiosis indicator is assigned to each position of the genome for each meiosis in a pedigree.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetic-linkage] The indicator indicates which copy of the parental chromosome contributes to the transmitted gamete at that position.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetic-linkage] For example, if the allele from the 'first' copy of the parental chromosome is transmitted, a '0' might be assigned to that meiosis.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetic-linkage] If the allele from the 'second' copy of the parental chromosome is transmitted, a '1' would be assigned to that meiosis.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetic-linkage] The two alleles in the parent came, one each, from two grandparents.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetic-linkage] These indicators are then used to determine identical-by-descent (IBD) states or inheritance states, which are in turn used to identify genes responsible for diseases.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] Trait inheritance and molecular inheritance mechanisms of genes are still primary principles of genetics in the 21st century, but modern genetics has expanded to study the function and behavior of genes.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] Gene structure and function, variation, and distribution are studied within the context of the cell, the organism (e.g. dominance), and within the context of a population.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] Genetics has given rise to a number of subfields, including molecular genetics, epigenetics, population genetics, and paleogenetics.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] Organisms studied within the broad field span the domains of life (archaea, bacteria, and eukarya).
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] Genetic processes work in combination with an organism's environment and experiences to influence development and behavior, often referred to as nature versus nurture.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] The intracellular or extracellular environment of a living cell or organism may increase or decrease gene transcription.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] A classic example is two seeds of genetically identical corn, one placed in a temperate climate and one in an arid climate (lacking sufficient waterfall or rain).
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] While the average height the two corn stalks could grow to is genetically determined, the one in the arid climate only grows to half the height of the one in the temperate climate due to lack of water and nutrients in its environment.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] William Bateson coined *genetics* from the ancient Greek γενετικός **genetikos** meaning "genitive"/"generative", which in turn derives from γένεσις **genesis** meaning "origin".
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] The observation that living things inherit traits from their parents has been used since prehistoric times to improve crop plants and animals through selective breeding.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] The modern science of genetics, seeking to understand this process, began with the work of the Augustinian friar Gregor Mendel in the mid-19th century.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] Prior to Mendel, Imre Festetics, a Hungarian noble, who lived in Kőszeg before Mendel, was the first who used the word "genetic" in hereditarian context, and is considered the first geneticist.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] He described several rules of biological inheritance in his work *The genetic laws of nature* (Die genetischen Gesetze der Natur, 1819).
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] His second law is the same as that which Mendel published.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] In his third law, he developed the basic principles of mutation (he can be considered a forerunner of Hugo de Vries).
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] Festetics argued that changes observed in the generation of farm animals, plants, and humans are the result of scientific laws.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] Festetics empirically deduced that organisms inherit their characteristics, not acquire them.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] He recognized recessive traits and inherent variation by postulating that traits of past generations could reappear later, and organisms could produce progeny with different attributes.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] These observations represent an important prelude to Mendel's theory of particulate inheritance insofar as it features a transition of heredity from its status as myth to that of a scientific discipline, by providing a fundamental theoretical basis for genetics in the twentieth century.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] Other theories of inheritance preceded Mendel's work.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] A popular theory during the 19th century, and implied by Charles Darwin's 1859 *On the Origin of Species*, was blending inheritance: the idea that individuals inherit a smooth blend of traits from their parents.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] Mendel's work provided examples where traits were definitely not blended after hybridization, showing that traits are produced by combinations of distinct genes rather than a continuous blend.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] Blending of traits in the progeny is now explained by the action of multiple genes with quantitative effects.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] Another theory that had some support at that time was the inheritance of acquired characteristics: the belief that individuals inherit traits strengthened by their parents.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] This theory (commonly associated with Jean-Baptiste Lamarck) is now known to be wrong—the experiences of individuals do not affect the genes they pass to their children.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] Other theories included Darwin's pangenesis (which had both acquired and inherited aspects) and Francis Galton's reformulation of pangenesis as both particulate and inherited.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] Modern genetics started with Mendel's studies of the nature of inheritance in plants.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] In his paper "*Versuche über Pflanzenhybriden*" ("Experiments on Plant Hybridization"), presented in 1865 to the *Naturforschender Verein* (Society for Research in Nature) in Brno, Mendel traced the inheritance patterns of certain traits in pea plants and described them mathematically.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] Although this pattern of inheritance could only be observed for a few traits, Mendel's work suggested that heredity was particulate, not acquired, and that the inheritance patterns of many traits could be explained through simple rules and ratios.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] The importance of Mendel's work did not gain wide understanding until 1900, after his death, when Hugo de Vries and other scientists rediscovered his research.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] William Bateson, a proponent of Mendel's work, coined the word *genetics* in 1905.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] The adjective *genetic*, derived from the Greek word *genesis*—γένεσις, "origin", predates the noun and was first used in a biological sense in 1860.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] Bateson both acted as a mentor and was aided significantly by the work of other scientists from Newnham College at Cambridge, specifically the work of Becky Saunders, Nora Darwin Barlow, and Muriel Wheldale Onslow.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] Bateson popularized the usage of the word *genetics* to describe the study of inheritance in his inaugural address to the Third International Conference on Plant Hybridization in London in 1906.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] After the rediscovery of Mendel's work, scientists tried to determine which molecules in the cell were responsible for inheritance.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] In 1900, Nettie Stevens began studying the mealworm.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] Over the next 11 years, she discovered that females only had the X chromosome and males had both X and Y chromosomes.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] She was able to conclude that sex is a chromosomal factor and is determined by the male.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] In 1911, Thomas Hunt Morgan argued that genes are on chromosomes, based on observations of a sex-linked white eye mutation in fruit flies.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] In 1913, his student Alfred Sturtevant used the phenomenon of genetic linkage to show that genes are arranged linearly on the chromosome.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] Although genes were known to exist on chromosomes, chromosomes are composed of both protein and DNA, and scientists did not know which of the two was responsible for inheritance.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] In 1928, Frederick Griffith discovered the phenomenon of transformation: dead bacteria could transfer genetic material to "transform" other still-living bacteria.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] Sixteen years later, in 1944, the Avery–MacLeod–McCarty experiment identified DNA as the molecule responsible for transformation.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] The role of the nucleus as the repository of genetic information in eukaryotes had been established by Hämmerling in 1943 in his work on the single celled alga *Acetabularia*.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] The Hershey–Chase experiment in 1952 confirmed that DNA (rather than protein) is the genetic material of the viruses that infect bacteria, providing further evidence that DNA is the molecule responsible for inheritance.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] James Watson and Francis Crick determined the structure of DNA in 1953, using the X-ray crystallography work of Rosalind Franklin and Maurice Wilkins that indicated DNA has a helical structure (i.e., shaped like a corkscrew).
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] Their double-helix model had two strands of DNA with the nucleotides pointing inward, each matching a complementary nucleotide on the other strand to form what look like rungs on a twisted ladder.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] This structure showed that genetic information exists in the sequence of nucleotides on each strand of DNA.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] The structure also suggested a simple method for replication: if the strands are separated, new partner strands can be reconstructed for each based on the sequence of the old strand.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] This property is what gives DNA its semi-conservative nature where one strand of new DNA is from an original parent strand.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] Although the structure of DNA showed how inheritance works, it was still not known how DNA influences the behavior of cells.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] In the following years, scientists tried to understand how DNA controls the process of protein production.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] It was discovered that the cell uses DNA as a template to create matching messenger RNA, molecules with nucleotides very similar to DNA.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] The nucleotide sequence of a messenger RNA is used to create an amino acid sequence in protein; this translation between nucleotide sequences and amino acid sequences is known as the genetic code.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] With the newfound molecular understanding of inheritance came an explosion of research.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] A notable theory arose from Tomoko Ohta in 1973 with her amendment to the neutral theory of molecular evolution through publishing the nearly neutral theory of molecular evolution.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] In this theory, Ohta stressed the importance of natural selection and the environment to the rate at which genetic evolution occurs.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] One important development was chain-termination DNA sequencing in 1977 by Frederick Sanger.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] This technology allows scientists to read the nucleotide sequence of a DNA molecule.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] In 1983, Kary Banks Mullis developed the polymerase chain reaction, providing a quick way to isolate and amplify a specific section of DNA from a mixture.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] The efforts of the Human Genome Project, Department of Energy, NIH, and parallel private efforts by Celera Genomics led to the sequencing of the human genome in 2003.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] At its most fundamental level, inheritance in organisms occurs by passing discrete heritable units, called genes, from parents to offspring.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] This property was first observed by Gregor Mendel, who studied the segregation of heritable traits in pea plants, showing for example that flowers on a single plant were either purple or white—but never an intermediate between the two colors.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] The discrete versions of the same gene controlling the inherited appearance (phenotypes) are called alleles.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] In the case of the pea, which is a diploid species, each individual plant has two copies of each gene, one copy inherited from each parent.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] Many species, including humans, have this pattern of inheritance.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] Diploid organisms with two copies of the same allele of a given gene are called homozygous at that gene locus, while organisms with two different alleles of a given gene are called heterozygous.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] The set of alleles for a given organism is called its genotype, while the observable traits of the organism are called its phenotype.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] When organisms are heterozygous at a gene, often one allele is called dominant as its qualities dominate the phenotype of the organism, while the other allele is called recessive as its qualities recede and are not observed.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] Some alleles do not have complete dominance and instead have incomplete dominance by expressing an intermediate phenotype, or codominance by expressing both alleles at once.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] When a pair of organisms reproduce sexually, their offspring randomly inherit one of the two alleles from each parent.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] These observations of discrete inheritance and the segregation of alleles are collectively known as Mendel's first law or the Law of Segregation.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] However, the probability of getting one gene over the other can change due to dominant, recessive, homozygous, or heterozygous genes.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] For example, Mendel found that if you cross heterozygous organisms your odds of getting the dominant trait is 3:1.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] Real geneticist study and calculate probabilities by using theoretical probabilities, empirical probabilities, the product rule, the sum rule, and more.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] Geneticists use diagrams and symbols to describe inheritance.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] A gene is represented by one or a few letters.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] Often a "+" symbol is used to mark the usual, non-mutant allele for a gene.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] In fertilization and breeding experiments (and especially when discussing Mendel's laws) the parents are referred to as the "P" generation and the offspring as the "F1" (first filial) generation.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] When the F1 offspring mate with each other, the offspring are called the "F2" (second filial) generation.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] One of the common diagrams used to predict the result of cross-breeding is the Punnett square.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] When studying human genetic diseases, geneticists often use pedigree charts to represent the inheritance of traits.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] These charts map the inheritance of a trait in a family tree.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] Organisms have thousands of genes, and in sexually reproducing organisms these genes generally assort independently of each other.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] This means that the inheritance of an allele for yellow or green pea color is unrelated to the inheritance of alleles for white or purple flowers.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] This phenomenon, known as "Mendel's law of independent assortment, means that the alleles of different genes get shuffled between parents to form offspring with many different combinations.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] Different genes often interact to influence the same trait.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] In the Blue-eyed Mary (*Omphalodes verna*), for example, there exists a gene with alleles that determine the color of flowers: blue or magenta.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] Another gene, however, controls whether the flowers have color at all or are white.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] When a plant has two copies of this white allele, its flowers are white—regardless of whether the first gene has blue or magenta alleles.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] This interaction between genes is called epistasis, with the second gene epistatic to the first.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] Many traits are not discrete features (e.g. purple or white flowers) but are instead continuous features (e.g. human height and skin color).
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] These complex traits are products of many genes.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] The influence of these genes is mediated, to varying degrees, by the environment an organism has experienced.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] The degree to which an organism's genes contribute to a complex trait is called heritability.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] Measurement of the heritability of a trait is relative—in a more variable environment, the environment has a bigger influence on the total variation of the trait.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] For example, human height is a trait with complex causes.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] It has a heritability of 89% in the United States.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] In Nigeria, however, where people experience a more variable access to good nutrition and health care, height has a heritability of only 62%.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] The molecular basis for genes is deoxyribonucleic acid (DNA).
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] DNA is composed of deoxyribose (sugar molecule), a phosphate group, and a base (amine group).
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] There are four types of bases: adenine (A), cytosine (C), guanine (G), and thymine (T).
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] The phosphates make phosphodiester bonds with the sugars to make long phosphate-sugar backbones.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] Bases specifically pair together (T&A, C&G) between two backbones and make like rungs on a ladder.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] The bases, phosphates, and sugars together make a nucleotide that connects to make long chains of DNA.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] Genetic information exists in the sequence of these nucleotides, and genes exist as stretches of sequence along the DNA chain.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] These chains coil into a double a-helix structure and wrap around proteins called Histones which provide the structural support.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] DNA wrapped around these histones are called chromosomes.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] Viruses sometimes use the similar molecule RNA instead of DNA as their genetic material.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] DNA normally exists as a double-stranded molecule, coiled into the shape of a double helix.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] Each nucleotide in DNA preferentially pairs with its partner nucleotide on the opposite strand: A pairs with T, and C pairs with G.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] Thus, in its two-stranded form, each strand effectively contains all necessary information, redundant with its partner strand.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] This structure of DNA is the physical basis for inheritance: DNA replication duplicates the genetic information by splitting the strands and using each strand as a template for synthesis of a new partner strand.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] Genes are arranged linearly along long chains of DNA base-pair sequences.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] In bacteria, each cell usually contains a single circular genophore, while eukaryotic organisms (such as plants and animals) have their DNA arranged in multiple linear chromosomes.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] These DNA strands are often extremely long; the largest human chromosome, for example, is about 247 million base pairs in length.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] The DNA of a chromosome is associated with structural proteins that organize, compact, and control access to the DNA, forming a material called chromatin; in eukaryotes, chromatin is usually composed of nucleosomes, segments of DNA wound around cores of histone proteins.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] The full set of hereditary material in an organism (usually the combined DNA sequences of all chromosomes) is called the genome.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] DNA is most often found in the nucleus of cells, but Ruth Sager helped in the discovery of nonchromosomal genes found outside of the nucleus.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] In plants, these are often found in the chloroplasts and in other organisms, in the mitochondria.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] These nonchromosomal genes can still be passed on by either partner in sexual reproduction and they control a variety of hereditary characteristics that replicate and remain active throughout generations.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] While haploid organisms have only one copy of each chromosome, most animals and many plants are diploid, containing two of each chromosome and thus two copies of every gene.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] The two alleles for a gene are located on identical loci of the two homologous chromosomes, each allele inherited from a different parent.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] Many species have so-called sex chromosomes that determine the sex of each organism.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] In humans and many other animals, the Y chromosome contains the gene that triggers the development of the specifically male characteristics.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] In evolution, this chromosome has lost most of its content and also most of its genes, while the X chromosome is similar to the other chromosomes and contains many genes.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] This being said, Mary Frances Lyon discovered that there is X-chromosome inactivation during reproduction to avoid passing on twice as many genes to the offspring.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] Lyon's discovery led to the discovery of X-linked diseases.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] When cells divide, their full genome is copied and each daughter cell inherits one copy.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] This process, called mitosis, is the simplest form of reproduction and is the basis for asexual reproduction.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] Asexual reproduction can also occur in multicellular organisms, producing offspring that inherit their genome from a single parent.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] Offspring that are genetically identical to their parents are called clones.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] Eukaryotic organisms often use sexual reproduction to generate offspring that contain a mixture of genetic material inherited from two different parents.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] The process of sexual reproduction alternates between forms that contain single copies of the genome (haploid) and double copies (diploid).
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] Haploid cells fuse and combine genetic material to create a diploid cell with paired chromosomes.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] Diploid organisms form haploids by dividing, without replicating their DNA, to create daughter cells that randomly inherit one of each pair of chromosomes.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] Most animals and many plants are diploid for most of their lifespan, with the haploid form reduced to single cell gametes such as sperm or eggs.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] Although they do not use the haploid/diploid method of sexual reproduction, bacteria have many methods of acquiring new genetic information.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] Some bacteria can undergo conjugation, transferring a small circular piece of DNA to another bacterium.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] Bacteria can also take up raw DNA fragments found in the environment and integrate them into their genomes, a phenomenon known as transformation.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] These processes result in horizontal gene transfer, transmitting fragments of genetic information between organisms that would be otherwise unrelated.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] Natural bacterial transformation occurs in many bacterial species, and can be regarded as a sexual process for transferring DNA from one cell to another cell (usually of the same species).
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] Transformation requires the action of numerous bacterial gene products, and its primary adaptive function appears to be repair of DNA damages in the recipient cell.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] The diploid nature of chromosomes allows for genes on different chromosomes to assort independently or be separated from their homologous pair during sexual reproduction wherein haploid gametes are formed.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] In this way new combinations of genes can occur in the offspring of a mating pair.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] Genes on the same chromosome would theoretically never recombine.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] However, they do, via the cellular process of chromosomal crossover.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] During crossover, chromosomes exchange stretches of DNA, effectively shuffling the gene alleles between the chromosomes.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] This process of chromosomal crossover generally occurs during meiosis, a series of cell divisions that creates haploid cells.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] Meiotic recombination, particularly in microbial eukaryotes, appears to serve the adaptive function of repair of DNA damages.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] The first cytological demonstration of crossing over was performed by Harriet Creighton and Barbara McClintock in 1931.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] Their research and experiments on corn provided cytological evidence for the genetic theory that linked genes on paired chromosomes do in fact exchange places from one homolog to the other.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] The probability of chromosomal crossover occurring between two given points on the chromosome is related to the distance between the points.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] For an arbitrarily long distance, the probability of crossover is high enough that the inheritance of the genes is effectively uncorrelated.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] For genes that are closer together, however, the lower probability of crossover means that the genes demonstrate genetic linkage; alleles for the two genes tend to be inherited together.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] The amounts of linkage between a series of genes can be combined to form a linear linkage map that roughly describes the arrangement of the genes along the chromosome.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] Genes express their functional effect through the production of proteins, which are molecules responsible for most functions in the cell.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] Proteins are made up of one or more polypeptide chains, each composed of a sequence of amino acids.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] The DNA sequence of a gene is used to produce a specific amino acid sequence.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] This process begins with the production of an RNA molecule with a sequence matching the gene's DNA sequence, a process called transcription.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] This messenger RNA molecule then serves to produce a corresponding amino acid sequence through a process called translation.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] Each group of three nucleotides in the sequence, called a codon, corresponds either to one of the twenty possible amino acids in a protein or an instruction to end the amino acid sequence; this correspondence is called the genetic code.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] The flow of information is unidirectional: information is transferred from nucleotide sequences into the amino acid sequence of proteins, but it never transfers from protein back into the sequence of DNA—a phenomenon Francis Crick called the central dogma of molecular biology.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] The specific sequence of amino acids results in a unique three-dimensional structure for that protein, and the three-dimensional structures of proteins are related to their functions.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] Some are simple structural molecules, like the fibers formed by the protein collagen.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] Proteins can bind to other proteins and simple molecules, sometimes acting as enzymes by facilitating chemical reactions within the bound molecules (without changing the structure of the protein itself).
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] Protein structure is dynamic; the protein hemoglobin bends into slightly different forms as it facilitates the capture, transport, and release of oxygen molecules within mammalian blood.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] A single nucleotide difference within DNA can cause a change in the amino acid sequence of a protein.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] Because protein structures are the result of their amino acid sequences, some changes can dramatically change the properties of a protein by destabilizing the structure or changing the surface of the protein in a way that changes its interaction with other proteins and molecules.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] For example, sickle-cell anemia is a human genetic disease that results from a single base difference within the coding region for the β-globin section of hemoglobin, causing a single amino acid change that changes hemoglobin's physical properties.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] Sickle-cell versions of hemoglobin stick to themselves, stacking to form fibers that distort the shape of red blood cells carrying the protein.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] These sickle-shaped cells no longer flow smoothly through blood vessels, having a tendency to clog or degrade, causing the medical problems associated with this disease.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] Some DNA sequences are transcribed into RNA but are not translated into protein products—such RNA molecules are called non-coding RNA.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] In some cases, these products fold into structures which are involved in critical cell functions (e.g. ribosomal RNA and transfer RNA).
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] RNA can also have regulatory effects through hybridization interactions with other RNA molecules (such as microRNA).
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] Although genes contain all the information an organism uses to function, the environment plays an important role in determining the ultimate phenotypes an organism displays.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] The phrase "nature and nurture" refers to this complementary relationship.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] The phenotype of an organism depends on the interaction of genes and the environment.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] An interesting example is the coat coloration of the Siamese cat.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] In this case, the body temperature of the cat plays the role of the environment.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] The cat's genes code for dark hair, thus the hair-producing cells in the cat make cellular proteins resulting in dark hair.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] But these dark hair-producing proteins are sensitive to temperature (i.e. have a mutation causing temperature-sensitivity) and denature in higher-temperature environments, failing to produce dark-hair pigment in areas where the cat has a higher body temperature.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] In a low-temperature environment, however, the protein's structure is stable and produces dark-hair pigment normally.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] The protein remains functional in areas of skin that are colder—such as its legs, ears, tail, and face—so the cat has dark hair at its extremities.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] Environment plays a major role in effects of the human genetic disease phenylketonuria.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] The mutation that causes phenylketonuria disrupts the ability of the body to break down the amino acid phenylalanine, causing a toxic build-up of an intermediate molecule that, in turn, causes severe symptoms of progressive intellectual disability and seizures.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] However, if someone with the phenylketonuria mutation follows a strict diet that avoids this amino acid, they remain normal and healthy.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] A common method for determining how genes and environment ("nature and nurture") contribute to a phenotype involves studying identical and fraternal twins, or other siblings of multiple births.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] Identical siblings are genetically the same since they come from the same zygote.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] Meanwhile, fraternal twins are as genetically different from one another as normal siblings.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] By comparing how often a certain disorder occurs in a pair of identical twins to how often it occurs in a pair of fraternal twins, scientists can determine whether that disorder is caused by genetic or postnatal environmental factors.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] One famous example involved the study of the Genain quadruplets, who were identical quadruplets all diagnosed with schizophrenia.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] The genome of a given organism contains thousands of genes, but not all these genes need to be active at any given moment.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] A gene is expressed when it is being transcribed into mRNA and there exist many cellular methods of controlling the expression of genes such that proteins are produced only when needed by the cell.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] Transcription factors are regulatory proteins that bind to DNA, either promoting or inhibiting the transcription of a gene.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] Within the genome of *Escherichia coli* bacteria, for example, there exists a series of genes necessary for the synthesis of the amino acid tryptophan.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] However, when tryptophan is already available to the cell, these genes for tryptophan synthesis are no longer needed.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] The presence of tryptophan directly affects the activity of the genes—tryptophan molecules bind to the tryptophan repressor (a transcription factor), changing the repressor's structure such that the repressor binds to the genes.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] The tryptophan repressor blocks the transcription and expression of the genes, thereby creating negative feedback regulation of the tryptophan synthesis process.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] Differences in gene expression are especially clear within multicellular organisms, where cells all contain the same genome but have very different structures and behaviors due to the expression of different sets of genes.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] All the cells in a multicellular organism derive from a single cell, differentiating into variant cell types in response to external and intercellular signals and gradually establishing different patterns of gene expression to create different behaviors.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] Within eukaryotes, there exist structural features of chromatin that influence the transcription of genes, often in the form of modifications to DNA and chromatin that are stably inherited by daughter cells.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] These features are called "epigenetic" because they exist "on top" of the DNA sequence and retain inheritance from one cell generation to the next.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] Because of epigenetic features, different cell types grown within the same medium can retain very different properties.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] Although epigenetic features are generally dynamic over the course of development, some, like the phenomenon of paramutation, have multigenerational inheritance and exist as rare exceptions to the general rule of DNA as the basis for inheritance.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] During the process of DNA replication, errors occasionally occur in the polymerization of the second strand.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] These errors, called mutations, can affect the phenotype of an organism, especially if they occur within the protein coding sequence of a gene.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] Error rates are usually very low—1 error in every 10–100 million bases—due to the "proofreading" ability of DNA polymerases.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] Processes that increase the rate of changes in DNA are called mutagenic: mutagenic chemicals promote errors in DNA replication, often by interfering with the structure of base-pairing, while UV radiation induces mutations by causing damage to the DNA structure.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] Chemical damage to DNA occurs naturally as well and cells use DNA repair mechanisms to repair mismatches and breaks.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] The repair does not, however, always restore the original sequence.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] A particularly important source of DNA damages appears to be reactive oxygen species produced by cellular aerobic respiration, and these can lead to mutations.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] In organisms that use chromosomal crossover to exchange DNA and recombine genes, errors in alignment during meiosis can also cause mutations.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] Errors in crossover are especially likely when similar sequences cause partner chromosomes to adopt a mistaken alignment; this makes some regions in genomes more prone to mutating in this way.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] These errors create large structural changes in DNA sequence—duplications, inversions, deletions of entire regions—or the accidental exchange of whole parts of sequences between different chromosomes, chromosomal translocation.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] Mutations alter an organism's genotype and occasionally this causes different phenotypes to appear.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] Most mutations have little effect on an organism's phenotype, health, or reproductive fitness.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] Mutations that do have an effect are usually detrimental, but occasionally some can be beneficial.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] Studies in the fly *Drosophila melanogaster* suggest that if a mutation changes a protein produced by a gene, about 70 percent of these mutations are harmful with the remainder being either neutral or weakly beneficial.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] Population genetics studies the distribution of genetic differences within populations and how these distributions change over time.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] Changes in the frequency of an allele in a population are mainly influenced by natural selection, where a given allele provides a selective or reproductive advantage to the organism, as well as other factors such as mutation, genetic drift, genetic hitchhiking, artificial selection and migration.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] Over many generations, the genomes of organisms can change significantly, resulting in evolution.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] In the process called adaptation, selection for beneficial mutations can cause a species to evolve into forms better able to survive in their environment.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] New species are formed through the process of speciation, often caused by geographical separations that prevent populations from exchanging genes with each other.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] By comparing the homology between different species' genomes, it is possible to calculate the evolutionary distance between them and when they may have diverged.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] Genetic comparisons are generally considered a more accurate method of characterizing the relatedness between species than the comparison of phenotypic characteristics.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] Although geneticists originally studied inheritance in a wide variety of organisms, the range of species studied has narrowed.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] One reason is that when significant research already exists for a given organism, new researchers are more likely to choose it for further study, and so eventually a few model organisms became the basis for most genetics research.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] Common research topics in model organism genetics include the study of gene regulation and the involvement of genes in development and cancer.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] Organisms were chosen, in part, for convenience—short generation times and easy genetic manipulation made some organisms popular genetics research tools.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] Medical genetics seeks to understand how genetic variation relates to human health and disease.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] When searching for an unknown gene that may be involved in a disease, researchers commonly use genetic linkage and genetic pedigree charts to find the location on the genome associated with the disease.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] At the population level, researchers take advantage of genome wide association studies (GWAS) to look for locations in the genome that are associated with diseases, a method especially useful for multigenic traits not clearly defined by a single gene.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] Once a candidate gene is found, further research is often done on the corresponding (or homologous) genes of model organisms.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] In addition to studying genetic diseases, the increased availability of genotyping methods has led to the field of pharmacogenetics: the study of how genotype can affect drug responses.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] Individuals differ in their inherited tendency to develop cancer, and cancer is a genetic disease.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] The process of cancer development in the body is a combination of events.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] Mutations occasionally occur within cells in the body as they divide.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] Although these mutations will not be inherited by any offspring, they can affect the behavior of cells, sometimes causing them to grow and divide more frequently.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] There are biological mechanisms that attempt to stop this process; signals are given to inappropriately dividing cells that should trigger cell death, but sometimes additional mutations occur that cause cells to ignore these messages.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] An internal process of natural selection occurs within the body and eventually mutations accumulate within cells to promote their own growth, creating a cancerous tumor that grows and invades various tissues of the body.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] Normally, a cell divides only in response to signals called growth factors and stops growing once in contact with surrounding cells and in response to growth-inhibitory signals.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] It usually then divides a limited number of times and dies, staying within the epithelium where it is unable to migrate to other organs.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] To become a cancer cell, a cell has to accumulate mutations in a number of genes (three to seven).
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] A cancer cell can divide without growth factor and ignores inhibitory signals.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] Also, it is immortal and can grow indefinitely, even after it makes contact with neighboring cells.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] It may escape from the epithelium and ultimately from the primary tumor.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] Then, the escaped cell can cross the endothelium of a blood vessel and get transported by the bloodstream to colonize a new organ, forming deadly metastasis.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] The most frequent mutations are a loss of function of p53 protein, a tumor suppressor, or in the p53 pathway, and gain of function mutations in the Ras proteins, or in other oncogenes.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] DNA can be manipulated in the laboratory.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] Restriction enzymes are commonly used enzymes that cut DNA at specific sequences, producing predictable fragments of DNA.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] DNA fragments can be visualized through use of gel electrophoresis, which separates fragments according to their length.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] The use of ligation enzymes allows DNA fragments to be connected.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] By binding ("ligating") fragments of DNA together from different sources, researchers can create recombinant DNA, the DNA often associated with genetically modified organisms.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] Recombinant DNA is commonly used in the context of plasmids: short circular DNA molecules with a few genes on them.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] In the process known as molecular cloning, researchers can amplify the DNA fragments by inserting plasmids into bacteria and then culturing them on plates of agar (to isolate clones of bacteria cells).
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] "Cloning" can also refer to the various means of creating cloned ("clonal") organisms.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] DNA can also be amplified using a procedure called the polymerase chain reaction (PCR).
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] By using specific short sequences of DNA, PCR can isolate and exponentially amplify a targeted region of DNA.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] Because it can amplify from extremely small amounts of DNA, PCR is also often used to detect the presence of specific DNA sequences.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] DNA sequencing, one of the most fundamental technologies developed to study genetics, allows researchers to determine the sequence of nucleotides in DNA fragments.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] The technique of chain-termination sequencing, developed in 1977 by a team led by Frederick Sanger, is still routinely used to sequence DNA fragments.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] Using this technology, researchers have been able to study the molecular sequences associated with many human diseases.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] As sequencing has become less expensive, researchers have sequenced the genomes of many organisms using a process called genome assembly, which uses computational tools to stitch together sequences from many different fragments.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] These technologies were used to sequence the human genome in the Human Genome Project completed in 2003.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] New high-throughput sequencing technologies are dramatically lowering the cost of DNA sequencing, with many researchers hoping to bring the cost of resequencing a human genome down to a thousand dollars.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] Next-generation sequencing (or high-throughput sequencing) came about due to the ever-increasing demand for low-cost sequencing.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] These sequencing technologies allow the production of potentially millions of sequences concurrently.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] The large amount of sequence data available has created the subfield of genomics, research that uses computational tools to search for and analyze patterns in the full genomes of organisms.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] Genomics can also be considered a subfield of bioinformatics, which uses computational approaches to analyze large sets of biological data.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] On 19 March 2015, a group of leading biologists urged a worldwide ban on clinical use of methods, particularly the use of CRISPR and zinc finger, to edit the human genome in a way that can be inherited.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genetics] In April 2015, Chinese researchers reported results of basic research to edit the DNA of non-viable human embryos using CRISPR.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genotype] The **genotype** of an organism is its complete set of genetic material.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genotype] Genotype can also be used to refer to the alleles or variants an individual carries in a particular gene or genetic location.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genotype] The number of alleles an individual can have in a specific gene depends on the number of copies of each chromosome found in that species, also referred to as ploidy.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genotype] In diploid species like humans, two full sets of chromosomes are present, meaning each individual has two alleles for any given gene.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genotype] If both alleles are the same, the genotype is referred to as homozygous.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genotype] If the alleles are different, the genotype is referred to as heterozygous.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genotype] Genotype contributes to phenotype, the observable traits and characteristics in an individual or organism.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genotype] The degree to which genotype affects phenotype depends on the trait.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genotype] For example, the petal color in a pea plant is exclusively determined by genotype.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genotype] The petals can be purple or white depending on the alleles present in the pea plant.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genotype] However, other traits are only partially influenced by genotype.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genotype] These traits are often called complex traits because they are influenced by additional factors, such as environmental and epigenetic factors.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genotype] Not all individuals with the same genotype look or act the same way because appearance and behavior are modified by environmental and growing conditions.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genotype] Likewise, not all organisms that look alike necessarily have the same genotype.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genotype] The term *genotype* was coined by the Danish botanist Wilhelm Johannsen in 1903.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genotype] Any given gene will usually cause an observable change in an organism, known as the phenotype.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genotype] A simple example to illustrate genotype as distinct from phenotype is the flower colour in pea plants (see Gregor Mendel).
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genotype] There are three available genotypes, PP (homozygous dominant), Pp (heterozygous), and pp (homozygous recessive).
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genotype] All three have different genotypes but the first two have the same phenotype (purple) as distinct from the third (white).
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genotype] A more technical example to illustrate genotype is the single-nucleotide polymorphism or SNP.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genotype] A SNP occurs when corresponding sequences of DNA from different individuals differ at one DNA base, for example where the sequence AAGCCTA changes to AAGCTTA.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genotype] SNPs typically have three genotypes, denoted generically AA Aa and aa.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genotype] In the example above, the three genotypes would be CC, CT and TT.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genotype] Other types of genetic marker, such as microsatellites, can have more than two alleles, and thus many different genotypes.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genotype] Penetrance is the proportion of individuals showing a specified genotype in their phenotype under a given set of environmental conditions.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genotype] Traits that are determined exclusively by genotype are typically inherited in a Mendelian pattern.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genotype] These laws of inheritance were described extensively by Gregor Mendel, who performed experiments with pea plants to determine how traits were passed on from generation to generation.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genotype] He studied phenotypes that were easily observed, such as plant height, petal color, or seed shape.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genotype] He was able to observe that if he crossed two true-breeding plants with distinct phenotypes, all the offspring would have the same phenotype.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genotype] For example, when he crossed a tall plant with a short plant, all the resulting plants would be tall.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genotype] However, when he self-fertilized the plants that resulted, about 1/4 of the second generation would be short.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genotype] He concluded that some traits were dominant, such as tall height, and others were recessive, like short height.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genotype] Though Mendel was not aware at the time, each phenotype he studied was controlled by a single gene with two alleles.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genotype] In the case of plant height, one allele caused the plants to be tall, and the other caused plants to be short.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genotype] When the tall allele was present, the plant would be tall, even if the plant was heterozygous.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genotype] In order for the plant to be short, it had to be homozygous for the recessive allele.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genotype] One way this can be illustrated is using a Punnett square.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genotype] In a Punnett square, the genotypes of the parents are placed on the outside.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genotype] An uppercase letter is typically used to represent the dominant allele, and a lowercase letter is used to represent the recessive allele.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genotype] The possible genotypes of the offspring can then be determined by combining the parent genotypes.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genotype] In the example on the right, both parents are heterozygous, with a genotype of Bb.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genotype] The offspring can inherit a dominant allele from each parent, making them homozygous with a genotype of BB.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genotype] The offspring can inherit a dominant allele from one parent and a recessive allele from the other parent, making them heterozygous with a genotype of Bb.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genotype] Finally, the offspring could inherit a recessive allele from each parent, making them homozygous with a genotype of bb.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genotype] Plants with the BB and Bb genotypes will look the same, since the B allele is dominant.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genotype] The plant with the bb genotype will have the recessive trait.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genotype] These inheritance patterns can also be applied to hereditary diseases or conditions in humans or animals.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genotype] Some conditions are inherited in an autosomal dominant pattern, meaning individuals with the condition typically have an affected parent as well.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genotype] A classic pedigree for an autosomal dominant condition shows affected individuals in every generation.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genotype] Other conditions are inherited in an autosomal recessive pattern, where affected individuals do not typically have an affected parent.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genotype] Since each parent must have a copy of the recessive allele in order to have an affected offspring, the parents are referred to as carriers of the condition.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genotype] In autosomal conditions, the sex of the offspring does not play a role in their risk of being affected.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genotype] In sex-linked conditions, the sex of the offspring affects their chances of having the condition.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genotype] In humans, females inherit two X chromosomes, one from each parent, while males inherit an X chromosome from their mother and a Y chromosome from their father.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genotype] X-linked dominant conditions can be distinguished from autosomal dominant conditions in pedigrees by the lack of transmission from fathers to sons, since affected fathers only pass their X chromosome to their daughters.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genotype] In X-linked recessive conditions, males are typically affected more commonly because they are hemizygous, with only one X chromosome.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genotype] In females, the presence of a second X chromosome will prevent the condition from appearing.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genotype] Females are therefore carriers of the condition and can pass the trait on to their sons.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genotype] Mendelian patterns of inheritance can be complicated by additional factors.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genotype] Some diseases show incomplete penetrance, meaning not all individuals with the disease-causing allele develop signs or symptoms of the disease.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genotype] Penetrance can also be age-dependent, meaning signs or symptoms of disease are not visible until later in life.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genotype] For example, Huntington disease is an autosomal dominant condition, but up to 25% of individuals with the affected genotype will not develop symptoms until after age 50.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genotype] Another factor that can complicate Mendelian inheritance patterns is variable expressivity, in which individuals with the same genotype show different signs or symptoms of disease.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genotype] For example, individuals with polydactyly can have a variable number of extra digits.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genotype] Many traits are not inherited in a Mendelian fashion, but have more complex patterns of inheritance.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genotype] For some traits, neither allele is completely dominant.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genotype] Heterozygotes often have an appearance somewhere in between those of homozygotes.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genotype] For example, a cross between true-breeding red and white *Mirabilis jalapa* results in pink flowers.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genotype] Codominance refers to traits in which both alleles are expressed in the offspring in approximately equal amounts.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genotype] A classic example is the ABO blood group system in humans, where both the A and B alleles are expressed when they are present.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genotype] Individuals with the AB genotype have both A and B proteins expressed on their red blood cells.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genotype] Epistasis is when the phenotype of one gene is affected by one or more other genes.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genotype] This is often through some sort of masking effect of one gene on the other.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genotype] For example, the "A" gene codes for hair color, a dominant "A" allele codes for brown hair, and a recessive "a" allele codes for blonde hair, but a separate "B" gene controls hair growth, and a recessive "b" allele causes baldness.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genotype] If the individual has the BB or Bb genotype, then they produce hair and the hair color phenotype can be observed, but if the individual has a bb genotype, then the person is bald which masks the A gene entirely.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genotype] A polygenic trait is one whose phenotype is dependent on the additive effects of multiple genes.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genotype] The contributions of each of these genes are typically small and add up to a final phenotype with a large amount of variation.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genotype] A well studied example of this is the number of sensory bristles on a fly.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genotype] These types of additive effects is also the explanation for the amount of variation in human eye color.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genotype] Genotyping refers to the method used to determine an individual's genotype.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genotype] There are a variety of techniques that can be used to assess genotype.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genotype] The genotyping method typically depends on what information is being sought.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genotype] Many techniques initially require amplification of the DNA sample, which is commonly done using PCR.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genotype] Some techniques are designed to investigate specific SNPs or alleles in a particular gene or set of genes, such as whether an individual is a carrier for a particular condition.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genotype] This can be done via a variety of techniques, including allele specific oligonucleotide (ASO) probes or DNA sequencing.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genotype] Tools such as multiplex ligation-dependent probe amplification can also be used to look for duplications or deletions of genes or gene sections.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genotype] Other techniques are meant to assess a large number of SNPs across the genome, such as SNP arrays.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genotype] This type of technology is commonly used for genome-wide association studies.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genotype] Large-scale techniques to assess the entire genome are also available.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genotype] This includes karyotyping to determine the number of chromosomes an individual has and chromosomal microarrays to assess for large duplications or deletions in the chromosome.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genotype] More detailed information can be determined using exome sequencing, which provides the specific sequence of all DNA in the coding region of the genome, or whole genome sequencing, which sequences the entire genome including non-coding regions.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genotype] In linear models, the genotypes can be encoded in different manners.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genotype] Let us consider a biallelic locus with two possible alleles, encoded by ${\textstyle A}$ and a .
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genotype] We consider **A** to correspond to the dominant allele to the reference allele ${\textstyle a}$ .
[src:genetics-fundamentals/genotype] The following table details the different encoding.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/mendelian-inheritance] The principles of Mendelian inheritance were named for and first derived by Gregor Johann Mendel, a nineteenth-century Moravian monk who formulated his ideas after conducting simple hybridization experiments with pea plants *(Pisum sativum)* he had planted in the garden of his monastery.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/mendelian-inheritance] Between 1856 and 1863, Mendel cultivated and tested some 28,000 pea plants.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/mendelian-inheritance] From these experiments, he induced two generalizations which later became known as *Mendel's Principles of Heredity* or *Mendelian inheritance*.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/mendelian-inheritance] He described his experiments in a two-part paper, *Versuche über Pflanzen-Hybriden* (*Experiments on Plant Hybridization*), that he presented to the Brünn Natural History Society of Brno on 8 February and 8 March 1865, and which was published in 1866.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/mendelian-inheritance] Mendel's results were at first largely ignored.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/mendelian-inheritance] Although they were not completely unknown to biologists of the time, they were not seen as generally applicable, even by Mendel himself, who thought they only applied to certain categories of species or traits.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/mendelian-inheritance] In 1900, however, his work was "re-discovered" by three European scientists, Hugo de Vries, Carl Correns, and Erich von Tschermak.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/mendelian-inheritance] The exact nature of the "re-discovery" has been debated: De Vries published first on the subject, mentioning Mendel in a footnote, while Correns pointed out Mendel's priority after having read De Vries' paper and realizing that he himself did not have priority.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/mendelian-inheritance] De Vries may not have acknowledged truthfully how much of his knowledge of the laws came from his own work and how much came only after reading Mendel's paper.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/mendelian-inheritance] Later scholars have accused Von Tschermak of not truly understanding the results at all.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/mendelian-inheritance] Regardless, the "re-discovery" made Mendelism an important but controversial theory.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/mendelian-inheritance] Its most vigorous promoter in Europe was William Bateson, who coined the terms "genetics" and "allele" to describe many of its tenets.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/mendelian-inheritance] The model of heredity was contested by other biologists because it implied that heredity was discontinuous, in opposition to the apparently continuous variation observable for many traits.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/mendelian-inheritance] Many biologists also dismissed the theory because they were not sure it would apply to all species.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/mendelian-inheritance] Mendel's findings allowed scientists such as Fisher and J.B.S.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/mendelian-inheritance] Haldane to predict the expression of traits on the basis of mathematical probabilities.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/mendelian-inheritance] An important aspect of Mendel's success can be traced to his decision to start his crosses only with plants he demonstrated were true-breeding.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/mendelian-inheritance] He only measured discrete (binary) characteristics, such as color, shape, and position of the seeds, rather than quantitatively variable characteristics.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/mendelian-inheritance] He expressed his results numerically and subjected them to statistical analysis.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/mendelian-inheritance] His method of data analysis and his large sample size gave credibility to his data.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/mendelian-inheritance] He had the foresight to follow several successive generations (P, F1, F2, F3) of pea plants and record their variations.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/mendelian-inheritance] Finally, he performed "test crosses" (backcrossing descendants of the initial hybridization to the initial true-breeding lines) to reveal the presence and proportions of recessive characters.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/mendelian-inheritance] Punnett squares are a well known genetics tool that was created by an English geneticist, Reginald Punnett, which can visually demonstrate all the possible genotypes that an offspring can receive, given the genotypes of their parents.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/mendelian-inheritance] Each parent carries two alleles, which can be shown on the top and the side of the chart, and each contribute one of them towards reproduction at a time.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/mendelian-inheritance] Each of the squares in the middle demonstrates the number of times each pairing of parental alleles could combine to make potential offspring.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/mendelian-inheritance] Using probabilities, one can then determine which genotypes the parents can create, and at what frequencies they can be created.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/mendelian-inheritance] For example, if two parents both have a heterozygous genotype, then there would be a 50% chance for their offspring to have the same genotype, and a 50% chance they would have a homozygous genotype.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/mendelian-inheritance] Since they could possibly contribute two identical alleles, the 50% would be halved to 25% to account for each type of homozygote, whether this was a homozygous dominant genotype, or a homozygous recessive genotype.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/mendelian-inheritance] Pedigrees are visual tree like representations that demonstrate exactly how alleles are being passed from past generations to future ones.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/mendelian-inheritance] They also provide a diagram displaying each individual that carries a desired allele, and exactly which side of inheritance it was received from, whether it was from their mother's side or their father's side.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/mendelian-inheritance] By using pedigrees, scientists have been able to find ways to control the flow of alleles over time, so that alleles that act problematic can be resolved upon discovery.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/mendelian-inheritance] Five parts of Mendel's discoveries were an important divergence from the common theories at the time and were the prerequisite for the establishment of his rules.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/mendelian-inheritance] Genetic characteristics have alternate forms, each inherited from one of two parents.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/mendelian-inheritance] The phenotype reflects the dominant allele.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/mendelian-inheritance] Gametes are created by random segregation.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/mendelian-inheritance] Heterozygotic individuals produce gametes with an equal frequency of the two alleles.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/mendelian-inheritance] Different traits have independent assortment.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/mendelian-inheritance] The laws were initially formulated by the geneticist Thomas Hunt Morgan in 1916.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/mendelian-inheritance] When he crossed purebred white flower and purple flower pea plants (the parental or P generation) by artificial pollination, the resulting flower colour was not a blend.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/mendelian-inheritance] Rather than being a mix of the two, the offspring in the first generation (F1-generation) were all purple-flowered.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/mendelian-inheritance] Therefore, he called this biological trait dominant.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/mendelian-inheritance] When he allowed self-fertilization in the uniform looking F1-generation, he obtained both colours in the F2 generation with a purple flower to white flower ratio of 3 : 1.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/mendelian-inheritance] In some of the other characters also one of the traits was dominant.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/mendelian-inheritance] He then conceived the idea of heredity units, which he called hereditary "factors".
[src:genetics-fundamentals/mendelian-inheritance] Mendel found that there are alternative forms of factors—now called genes—that account for variations in inherited characteristics.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/mendelian-inheritance] For example, the gene for flower color in pea plants exists in two forms, one for purple and the other for white.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/mendelian-inheritance] The alternative "forms" are now called alleles.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/mendelian-inheritance] For each trait, an organism inherits two alleles, one from each parent.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/mendelian-inheritance] These alleles may be the same or different.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/mendelian-inheritance] An organism that has two identical alleles for a gene is said to be homozygous for that gene (and is called a homozygote).
[src:genetics-fundamentals/mendelian-inheritance] An organism that has two different alleles for a gene is said to be heterozygous for that gene (and is called a heterozygote).
[src:genetics-fundamentals/mendelian-inheritance] Mendel hypothesized that allele pairs separate randomly, or segregate, from each other during the production of the gametes in the seed plant (egg cell) and the pollen plant (sperm).
[src:genetics-fundamentals/mendelian-inheritance] Because allele pairs separate during gamete production, a sperm or egg carries only one allele for each inherited trait.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/mendelian-inheritance] When sperm and egg unite at fertilization, each contributes its allele, restoring the paired condition in the offspring.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/mendelian-inheritance] Mendel also found that each pair of alleles segregates independently of the other pairs of alleles during gamete formation.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/mendelian-inheritance] The genotype of an individual is made up of the many alleles it possesses.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/mendelian-inheritance] The phenotype is the result of the expression of all characteristics that are genetically determined by its alleles as well as by its environment.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/mendelian-inheritance] The presence of an allele does not mean that the trait will be expressed in the individual that possesses it.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/mendelian-inheritance] If the two alleles of an inherited pair differ (the heterozygous condition), then one determines the organism's appearance and is called the dominant allele; the other has no noticeable effect on the organism's appearance and is called the recessive allele.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/mendelian-inheritance] If two parents are mated with each other who differ in one genetic characteristic for which they are both homozygous (each pure-bred), all offspring in the first generation (F1) are equal to the examined characteristic in genotype and phenotype showing the dominant trait.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/mendelian-inheritance] This *uniformity rule* or *reciprocity rule* applies to all individuals of the F1-generation.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/mendelian-inheritance] The principle of dominant inheritance discovered by Mendel states that in a heterozygote the dominant allele will cause the recessive allele to be "masked": that is, not expressed in the phenotype.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/mendelian-inheritance] Only if an individual is homozygous with respect to the recessive allele will the recessive trait be expressed.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/mendelian-inheritance] Therefore, a cross between a homozygous dominant and a homozygous recessive organism yields a heterozygous organism whose phenotype displays only the dominant trait.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/mendelian-inheritance] The F1 offspring of Mendel's pea crosses always looked like one of the two parental varieties.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/mendelian-inheritance] In this situation of "complete dominance", the dominant allele had the same phenotypic effect whether present in one or two copies.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/mendelian-inheritance] But for some characteristics, the F1 hybrids have an appearance *in between* the phenotypes of the two parental varieties.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/mendelian-inheritance] A cross between two four o'clock (*Mirabilis jalapa*) plants shows an exception to Mendel's principle, called *incomplete dominance*.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/mendelian-inheritance] Flowers of heterozygous plants have a phenotype somewhere between the two homozygous genotypes.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/mendelian-inheritance] In cases of intermediate inheritance (incomplete dominance) in the F1-generation Mendel's principle of uniformity in genotype and phenotype applies as well.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/mendelian-inheritance] Research about intermediate inheritance was done by other scientists.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/mendelian-inheritance] The first was Carl Correns with his studies about Mirabilis jalapa.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/mendelian-inheritance] The law of segregation of genes applies when two individuals, both heterozygous for a certain trait, are crossed: for example, hybrids of the F1-generation.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/mendelian-inheritance] The offspring in the F2-generation differ in genotype and phenotype so that the characteristics of the grandparents (P-generation) regularly occur again.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/mendelian-inheritance] In a dominant-recessive inheritance, an average of 25% are homozygous with the dominant trait, 50% are heterozygous showing the dominant trait in the phenotype (genetic carriers), 25% are homozygous with the recessive trait and therefore express the recessive trait in the phenotype.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/mendelian-inheritance] The genotypic ratio is 1: 2 : 1, and the phenotypic ratio is 3: 1.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/mendelian-inheritance] In the pea plant example, the capital "B" represents the dominant allele for purple blossom and lowercase "b" represents the recessive allele for white blossom.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/mendelian-inheritance] The pistil plant and the pollen plant are both F1-hybrids with genotype "B b".
[src:genetics-fundamentals/mendelian-inheritance] Each has one allele for purple and one allele for white.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/mendelian-inheritance] In the offspring, in the F2-plants in the Punnett-square, three combinations are possible.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/mendelian-inheritance] The genotypic ratio is 1 *BB* : 2 *Bb* : 1 *bb*.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/mendelian-inheritance] But the phenotypic ratio of plants with purple blossoms to those with white blossoms is 3 : 1 due to the dominance of the allele for purple.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/mendelian-inheritance] Plants with homozygous "b b" are white flowered like one of the grandparents in the P-generation.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/mendelian-inheritance] This results in an intermediate inheritance which was later described by other scientists.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/mendelian-inheritance] In some literature sources, the principle of segregation is cited as the "first law".
[src:genetics-fundamentals/mendelian-inheritance] Nevertheless, Mendel did his crossing experiments with heterozygous plants after obtaining these hybrids by crossing two purebred plants, discovering the principle of dominance and uniformity first.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/mendelian-inheritance] Molecular proof of segregation of genes was subsequently found through observation of meiosis by two scientists independently, the German botanist Oscar Hertwig in 1876, and the Belgian zoologist Edouard Van Beneden in 1883.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/mendelian-inheritance] Most alleles are located in chromosomes in the cell nucleus.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/mendelian-inheritance] Paternal and maternal chromosomes get separated in meiosis because during spermatogenesis the chromosomes are segregated on the four sperm cells that arise from one mother sperm cell, and during oogenesis the chromosomes are distributed between the polar bodies and the egg cell.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/mendelian-inheritance] Every individual organism contains two alleles for each trait.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/mendelian-inheritance] They segregate (separate) during meiosis such that each gamete contains only one of the alleles.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/mendelian-inheritance] When the gametes unite in the zygote the alleles—one from the mother one from the father—get passed on to the offspring.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/mendelian-inheritance] An offspring thus receives a pair of alleles for a trait by inheriting homologous chromosomes from the parent organisms: one allele for each trait from each parent.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/mendelian-inheritance] Heterozygous individuals with the dominant trait in the phenotype are genetic carriers of the recessive trait.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/mendelian-inheritance] The law of independent assortment proposes alleles for separate traits are passed independently of one another.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/mendelian-inheritance] That is, the biological selection of an allele for one trait has nothing to do with the selection of an allele for any other trait.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/mendelian-inheritance] Mendel found support for this law in his dihybrid cross experiments.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/mendelian-inheritance] In his monohybrid crosses, an idealized 3:1 ratio between dominant and recessive phenotypes resulted.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/mendelian-inheritance] In dihybrid crosses, however, he found a 9:3:3:1 ratios.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/mendelian-inheritance] This shows that each of the two alleles is inherited independently from the other, with a 3:1 phenotypic ratio for each.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/mendelian-inheritance] Independent assortment occurs in eukaryotic organisms during meiotic metaphase I, and produces a gamete with a mixture of the organism's chromosomes.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/mendelian-inheritance] The physical basis of the independent assortment of chromosomes is the random orientation of each bivalent chromosome along the metaphase plate with respect to the other bivalent chromosomes.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/mendelian-inheritance] Along with crossing over, independent assortment increases genetic diversity by producing novel genetic combinations.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/mendelian-inheritance] There are many deviations from the principle of independent assortment due to genetic linkage.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/mendelian-inheritance] Of the 46 chromosomes in a normal diploid human cell, half are maternally derived (from the mother's egg) and half are paternally derived (from the father's sperm).
[src:genetics-fundamentals/mendelian-inheritance] This occurs as sexual reproduction involves the fusion of two haploid gametes (the egg and sperm) to produce a zygote and a new organism, in which every cell has two sets of chromosomes (diploid).
[src:genetics-fundamentals/mendelian-inheritance] During gametogenesis the normal complement of 46 chromosomes needs to be halved to 23 to ensure that the resulting haploid gamete can join with another haploid gamete to produce a diploid organism.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/mendelian-inheritance] In independent assortment, the chromosomes that result are randomly sorted from all possible maternal and paternal chromosomes.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/mendelian-inheritance] Because zygotes end up with a mix instead of a pre-defined "set" from either parent, chromosomes are therefore considered assorted independently.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/mendelian-inheritance] As such, the zygote can end up with any combination of paternal or maternal chromosomes.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/mendelian-inheritance] For human gametes, with 23 chromosomes, the number of possibilities is 223 or 8,388,608 possible combinations.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/mendelian-inheritance] This contributes to the genetic variability of progeny.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/mendelian-inheritance] Generally, the recombination of genes has important implications for many evolutionary processes.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/mendelian-inheritance] A Mendelian trait is one whose inheritance follows Mendel's principles—namely, the trait depends only on a single locus, whose alleles are either dominant or recessive.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/mendelian-inheritance] Many traits are inherited in a non-Mendelian fashion.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/mendelian-inheritance] Mendel himself warned that care was needed in extrapolating his patterns to other organisms or traits.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/mendelian-inheritance] Indeed, many organisms have traits whose inheritance works differently from the principles he described; these traits are called non-Mendelian.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/mendelian-inheritance] For example, Mendel focused on traits whose genes have only two alleles, such as "A" and "a".
[src:genetics-fundamentals/mendelian-inheritance] However, many genes have more than two alleles.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/mendelian-inheritance] He also focused on traits determined by a single gene.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/mendelian-inheritance] But some traits, such as height, depend on many genes rather than just one.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/mendelian-inheritance] Traits dependent on multiple genes are called polygenic traits.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/punnett-square] The **Punnett square** is a square diagram that is used to predict the genotypes of a particular cross or breeding experiment.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/punnett-square] Punnett, who devised the approach in 1905.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/punnett-square] The diagram is used by biologists to determine the probability of an offspring having a particular genotype.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/punnett-square] The Punnett square is a tabular summary of possible combinations of maternal alleles with paternal alleles.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/punnett-square] These tables can be used to examine the genotypical outcome probabilities of the offspring of a single trait (allele), or when crossing multiple traits from the parents.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/punnett-square] The Punnett square is a visual representation of Mendelian inheritance, a fundamental concept in genetics discovered by Gregor Mendel.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/punnett-square] For multiple traits, using the "forked-line method" is typically much easier than the Punnett square.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/punnett-square] Phenotypes may be predicted with at least better-than-chance accuracy using a Punnett square, but the phenotype that may appear in the presence of a given genotype can in some instances be influenced by many other factors, as when polygenic inheritance and/or epigenetics are at work.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/punnett-square] Zygosity refers to the grade of similarity between the alleles that determine one specific trait in an organism.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/punnett-square] In its simplest form, a pair of alleles can be either homozygous or heterozygous.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/punnett-square] Homozygosity, with *homo* relating to *same* while *zygous* pertains to a zygote, is seen when a combination of either two dominant or two recessive alleles code for the same trait.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/punnett-square] For example, using 'A' as the representative character for each allele, a homozygous dominant pair's genotype would be depicted as 'AA', while homozygous recessive is shown as 'aa'.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/punnett-square] Heterozygosity, with *hetero* associated with *different*, can only be 'Aa' (the capital letter is always presented first by convention).
[src:genetics-fundamentals/punnett-square] The phenotype of a homozygous dominant pair is 'A', or dominant, while the opposite is true for homozygous recessive.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/punnett-square] Heterozygous pairs always have a dominant phenotype.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/punnett-square] To a lesser degree, hemizygosity and nullizygosity can also be seen in gene pairs.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/punnett-square] "Mono-" means "one"; this cross indicates that the examination of a single trait.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/punnett-square] This could mean (for example) eye color.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/punnett-square] Each genetic locus is always represented by two letters.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/punnett-square] So in the case of eye color, say "B = Brown eyes" and "b = green eyes".
[src:genetics-fundamentals/punnett-square] In this example, both parents have the genotype *Bb*.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/punnett-square] For the example of eye color, this would mean they both have brown eyes.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/punnett-square] They can produce gametes that contain either the *B* or the *b* allele.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/punnett-square] (It is conventional in genetics to use capital letters to indicate dominant alleles and lower-case letters to indicate recessive alleles.) The probability of an individual offspring's having the genotype *BB* is 25%, *Bb* is 50%, and *bb* is 25%.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/punnett-square] The ratio of the phenotypes is 3:1, typical for a monohybrid cross.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/punnett-square] When assessing phenotype from this, 3 of the offspring have "Brown" eyes and only one offspring has "green" eyes.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/punnett-square] The way in which the *B* and *b* alleles interact with each other to affect the appearance of the offspring depends on how the gene products (proteins) interact (see Mendelian inheritance).
[src:genetics-fundamentals/punnett-square] This can include lethal effects and epistasis (where one allele masks another, regardless of dominant or recessive status).
[src:genetics-fundamentals/punnett-square] More complicated crosses can be made by looking at two or more genes.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/punnett-square] The Punnett square works, however, only if the genes are independent of each other, which means that having a particular allele of gene "A" does not alter the probability of possessing an allele of gene "B".
[src:genetics-fundamentals/punnett-square] This is equivalent to stating that the genes are not linked, so that the two genes do not tend to sort together during meiosis.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/punnett-square] The following example illustrates a dihybrid cross between two double-heterozygote pea plants.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/punnett-square] *R* represents the dominant allele for shape (round), while *r* represents the recessive allele (wrinkled).
[src:genetics-fundamentals/punnett-square] *Y* represents the dominant allele for color (yellow), while *y* represents the recessive allele (green).
[src:genetics-fundamentals/punnett-square] If each plant has the genotype *RrYy*, and since the alleles for shape and color genes are independent, then they can produce four types of gametes with all possible combinations: *RY*, *Ry*, *rY*, and *ry*.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/punnett-square] Since dominant traits mask recessive traits (assuming no epistasis), there are nine combinations that have the phenotype round yellow, three that are round green, three that are wrinkled yellow, and one that is wrinkled green.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/punnett-square] The ratio 9:3:3:1 is the expected outcome when crossing two double-heterozygous parents with unlinked genes.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/punnett-square] Any other ratio indicates that something else has occurred (such as lethal alleles, epistasis, linked genes, etc.).
[src:genetics-fundamentals/punnett-square] The forked-line method (also known as the tree method and the branching system) can also solve dihybrid and multi-hybrid crosses.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/punnett-square] A problem is converted to a series of monohybrid crosses, and the results are combined in a tree.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/punnett-square] However, a tree produces the same result as a Punnett square in less time and with more clarity.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/punnett-square] The example below assesses another double-heterozygote cross using RrYy x RrYy.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/punnett-square] As stated above, the phenotypic ratio is expected to be 9:3:3:1 if crossing unlinked genes from two double-heterozygotes.
[src:genetics-fundamentals/punnett-square] The genotypic ratio was obtained in the diagram below, this diagram will have more branches than if only analyzing for phenotypic ratio.
